European debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley -- "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think, but now it's not, because it's clearly a crisis of the Eurozone.
Dealing with it is both easier and more difficult than usually expected.
The economics of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has problems.
Spain has problems in all of the above three aspects.
Although the details vary, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to go through a painful process of spending cuts.
The usual way to offset the side effects of austerity is to combine domestic spending cuts with depreciation of the domestic currency.
Depreciation will enhance the competitiveness of exports, that is, using external demand to make up for internal demand.
However, these countries are all members of the Eurozone, and they do not have an independent domestic currency that can be devalued, so they can only use internal devaluation to replace external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have quite a strong determination to tighten their belts.
However, there is an economic variable that has not changed with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
The face value of accumulated government debt has not changed, and bank debt — except for some debt owed to junior creditors — has also basically remained unchanged.
It is this simple fact that puts the internal devaluation strategy in a self-contradictory position: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relatively.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending must be cut and taxes increased in order to deal with the debt of the government and its protectors (such as banks).
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, in order for the internal devaluation strategy to be effective, it is necessary to find a way to reduce the face value of the debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and when banks are insolvent, it should be written off.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers are reluctant to take this path.
Contracts are sacred.
Government is concerned about losing credibility in the financial markets.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-downs would only burden other countries.
These concerns are not without reason, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
There are only two ways out: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose between the two.
They unanimously ruled out the option of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is neither reasonable nor logical.
Debt restructuring is straightforward and clear-cut.
The government can issue a batch of debt instruments with face values discounted at a certain ratio from the current face value of the debt.
Bondholders can choose either to stick to their bonds and redeem them at face value, albeit with later maturity dates and lower interest rates; or accept discounted bonds with lower face values than existing bonds, but with earlier maturity dates and higher interest rates.
This is not some cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to make it work, there are three prerequisites.
First, it is necessary to guarantee the safety of the new bonds to bondholders.
Someone has to come forward to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin American debt restructuring was carried out under the Brady Plan, the United States Treasury played the role of the "guaranteeing elder brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act unanimously.
Otherwise, debt restructuring in one country would raise expectations in other countries, leading to a ripple effect.
Finally, banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must consolidate their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, not the bureaucratic formalities carried out earlier this year.
If debt restructuring indicates capital shortfalls, a complete conversion of debt into equity for the relevant banks is necessary.
If that is not enough, the government must inject capital into the relevant banks.
This too requires unanimous action by countries.
Once banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it will be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without shaking the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest difficulty.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
The German leaders must admit that their banks have large risk exposures to the debts of peripheral Eurozone countries, and the situation is critical.
They must convince their backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany has urged other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should shoulder the responsibility of guaranteeing it without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences sound more severe — otherwise, they will be in serious trouble.
Because that's just the way it is.
